In JavaScript, you can use the `localStorage` object to save data locally on a user's browser. To save data, you can use the `setItem()` method, and to read data back, you can use the `getItem()` method. Here's an example of how to do both:

1. Saving data to localStorage:
```javascript
// Save a string value
localStorage.setItem("key", "value");

// Save an object (JSON) value
const data = {
  name: "John Doe",
  age: 30,
  occupation: "Software Engineer"
};
localStorage.setItem("userData", JSON.stringify(data));
```

2. Reading data from localStorage:
```javascript
// Read a string value
const value = localStorage.getItem("key");
console.log(value); // Output: "value"

// Read an object (JSON) value
const storedData = JSON.parse(localStorage.getItem("userData"));
console.log(storedData);
/* Output:
{
  name: "John Doe",
  age: 30,
  occupation: "Software Engineer"
}
*/
```
Remember that the `localStorage` object is limited to a maximum of 5 MB per domain. Also, keep in mind that data stored in localStorage persists even after the browser is closed, which means it can be accessed by other tabs or windows from the same domain. If you want to delete an item from localStorage, use the `removeItem()` method:
```javascript
localStorage.removeItem("key");
```
Or clear all data for a specific domain:
```javascript
localStorage.clear();
```
